“First, to create a Streamlit app in Snowflake, I go to the left navigation menu and click Projects.
Under Projects, I select Streamlit. This page shows the list of Streamlit apps that already exist in the Snowflake account.
To create a new app, I click the + Streamlit App button on the top-right side.
Snowflake gives two options. One option is to create the app directly inside Snowflake. In this approach, we write and maintain the Streamlit code directly in the Snowflake editor itself.
The second option is to create the app from a repository. This means the Streamlit code is maintained outside Snowflake in a source control repository like GitHub, and then connected or deployed into Snowflake. This approach is usually used for larger or more complex applications with CI/CD and version control processes.
For this demo, I am creating the app directly inside Snowflake.
Next, I enter the app title. This name identifies the Streamlit application.
Then I select the app location, which includes the database and schema where the Streamlit app object will be created.
After that, I select the Python environment.
There are two options: Run on container and Run on warehouse.
Run on container is used for more advanced apps that need container compute, more package flexibility, or CPU/GPU support.
Run on warehouse is simpler and uses a Snowflake virtual warehouse to run the app. Since this app mainly connects to Snowflake tables and performs read and update operations, I select Run on warehouse.
Then I select the query warehouse. This is the warehouse Snowflake will use when the app runs queries against tables or views.
Once these details are selected, I click Create.
Snowflake then creates the Streamlit application and opens the app editor.
Inside the app, the main Python file is usually called:
streamlit_app.py
This is where the Streamlit UI code is written.
There is also an environment file, usually:
environment.yml
This file stores the Python package dependencies required for the app, such as Streamlit and Snowpark.
In the Python code, we import Streamlit to build the user interface, and we use Snowpark to connect to Snowflake using the active session.
For example, the app uses the active Snowflake session to read data from Snowflake tables, display it in the Streamlit screen, allow users to make updates, and then write the changed records back to Snowflake.
This is a very simple Streamlit app that is created directly inside Snowflake.
In the same way, we created the CFG_VW_CONTROL Streamlit application. We started with the basic Streamlit framework and then modified the Python code and Snowflake logic according to our specific use case and table requirements.”
